{"id":"2210.16837","submitter":"Marian Kupczynski","authors":"Marian Kupczynski","title":"My discussions with John Stuart Bell","comments":"14 pages + 124 referencs","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.hist-ph hep-th quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In 1976, I met John Bell several times in CERN and we talked about a possible\nviolation of optical theorem, purity tests, EPR paradox, Bell inequalities and\ntheir violation. I resume our discussions, and explain how they were related to\nmy earlier research. I also reproduce handwritten notes, which I gave to Bell\nduring our first meeting and a handwritten letter he sent to me in 1982. We\nhave never met again, but I have continued to discuss BI-CHSH inequalities and\ntheir violation in several papers. The research stimulated by Bell papers and\nexperiments performed to check his inequalities led to several important\napplications of quantum entanglement in quantum information and quantum\ntechnologies. Unfortunately, it led also to extraordinary metaphysical claims\nand speculations about quantum nonlocality and magic, which in our opinion John\nBell would not endorse today. BI-CHSH inequalities are violated in physics and\nin cognitive science, but as members of so called probabilistic opposition have\nclaimed for years, it neither proved the completeness of quantum mechanics nor\nits nonlocality. We hope that this year Nobel Prize laureates will explain\nthat: one has to be cautious in drawing far-reaching philosophical conclusions\nfrom Bell inequalities.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 30 Oct 2022 13:25:13 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-11-01"}
